'''Jeanne Randolph''' (born 1943) is a cultural critic, author, performance artist and psychiatrist whose work explores the relationship between art and psychoanalytic theory.<ref>{{cite book |title=Symbolism and its Discontents |last=Randolph |first=Jeanne |publisher=YYZ Books |year=1997 |isbn=0-920397-22-0 |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |pages=endnotes}}</ref> She was the first writer in Canada to develop [[Object relations theory|Object Relations]] psychoanalytic theory as a medium for [[cultural criticism]].<ref name="ASA">{{cite web |url=https://www.umanitoba.ca/schools/art/content/galleryoneoneone/asa04.html |title=Art School Anatomies |website=www.umanitoba.ca |access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> In universities and galleries across Canada, England, Australia and Spain she has spoken on topics ranging from the aesthetics of [[Barbie]] dolls to the philosophy of [[Ludwig Wittgenstein|Wittgenstein]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://artspeak.ca/jeanne-randolph/ |title=Jeanne Randolph {{!}} Artspeak |website=artspeak.ca |access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref>
== Books == Dr. Jeanne Randolph is the author of ''Shopping Cart Pantheism'' (2015),[https://alllitup.ca/books/S/Shopping-Cart-Pantheism] ''Joanne Todd'' (1989, currently out of print),<ref>{{cite book|title=Joanne Todd |last=Randolph |first=Jeanne |publisher=Art Gallery of Greater Victoria |year=1986 |isbn=<!--unknown--> |location=Victoria, British Columbia, Canada |pages=}}</ref> ''Psychoanalysis & Synchronized Swimming and Other Writings on Art'' (1991),<ref>{{cite book |title=Psychoanalysis & Synchronized Swimming and Other Writings on Art |last=Randolph |first=Jeanne |publisher=YYZ Books |year=1991 |isbn=978-0-920397-07-7 |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |pages=}}</ref> ''Symbolism and its Discontents'' (1997),<ref>{{cite book |title=Symbolism and its Discontents |last=Randolph |first=Jeanne |publisher=YYZ Books |year=1997 |isbn=0-920397-22-0 |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |pages=}}</ref> ''Why Stoics Box'' (2006)<ref>{{cite book |title=Why Stoics Box |last=Randolph |first=Jeanne |publisher=YYZ Books |year=2003 |isbn=0-920397-81-6 |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |pages=}}</ref> and ''Ethics of Luxury: Materialism and Imagination'' (2007),<ref>{{cite book |title=Ethics of Luxury: Materialism and Imagination |last=Randolph |first=Jeanne |publisher=YYZ Books |year=2007 |isbn=0-920397-46-8 |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |pages=}}</ref> and co-author of ''Semble: Lyn Carter, Ginette Legaré & [[Jeannie Thib]].''<ref>{{cite book |title=Semble: Lyn Carter, Ginette Legaré & Jeannie Thib |last1=Randolph |first1=Jeanne |last2=Gibson |first2=Susan |publisher=Dalhousie University Art Gallery |year=2002 |isbn=0-7703-2742-7 |location=Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada |pages=}}</ref> She has contributed essays to books about art and artists including ''Subconscious City'',<ref>{{cite book |title=Subconscious City |last1=Dempsey |first1=Shawna |last2=Millan |first2=Lorri |publisher=Winnipeg Art Gallery |year=2008 |isbn=0-88915-241-1 |location=Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada |pages=}}</ref> ''Susan Kealey: Ordinary Marvel''<ref>{{cite book |title=Susan Kealey: Ordinary Marvel |last=Rudder |first=Jennifer |publisher=YYZ Books |year=2003 |isbn=0-920397-83-2 |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |pages=}}</ref> and ''Robbin Deyo: Sweet Sensation''<ref>{{cite book |title=Robbin Deyo: Sweet Sensations |last=Deyo |first=Robbin |publisher=Southern Alberta Art Gallery |year=2005 |isbn=1-894699-31-9 |location=Lethbridge, Alberta, Canada |pages=}}</ref> among others.
== Performances == Randolph's lectures evolved into performances that have been presented in venues including the [[Dunlop Art Gallery]]'s ''Space Camp'' (2000),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dunlopartgallery.org/exhibitions/archives2000_17.html |title=Dunlop Art Gallery Exhibitions :: Space Camp 2000: Uncertainty, Speculative Fictions & Art |website=www.dunlopartgallery.org |access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> the [[Banff Centre|Banff Centre for the Arts]] (2004) and Gallery 1.1.1 (2008).<ref name="ASA" /> They have been described as, "extemporaneous soliloquies [that] illuminate and interpret traditional academic pedagogy, enacting criticism as a dynamic psychoanalytic and philosophical contribution to cultural objects".<ref name="ASA" />
